file.list <- list.files("../raw_data/infauna/community_data", full.names = T)

for (i in 1:length(file.list)){
  df <- read_csv(file.list[i]) %>% mutate(collection_number = as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9]", "",file.list[i])))

  if (i == 1){
      df_all <- df
  }
  
  if (i > 1){
    df_all <- df_all %>% full_join(df) #%>% mutate_all(~replace_na(.,0))
  }
}

# PLOT/ANALYSIS 1: Bncle recruitment in unshaded plot

barnacles <- all_visuals %>% filter(taxon_code %in% c("BAGL","CHDA", "SECA") & treatment %in% c(3, 4)) %>% mutate(date = as.Date(date))

summary.bncles <- all_visuals %>% group_by(date) %>% summarize(bncle_total = sum(abund)) %>% View()
View(barnacles)
# middle survey has the most recruitment signal

recruitment.peak <- barnacles %>% filter(date == "2021-07-07" | date == "2021-07-08") %>% group_by(plot_number, treatment_code) %>% summarize(total_abund = sum(abund)) %>% mutate(trt_long = case_when(treatment_code == "SR" ~ "shaded removal", treatment_code == "UR" ~ "unshaded removal"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'plot_number'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(recruitment.peak, aes(x = treatment_code, y = total_abund, col = trt_long)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(x = "Treatment", y = "Total barnacle abundance", col = "Treatment") + theme_bw() + scale_color_manual(values = c("skyblue2", "tomato2"))

mod.recruit <- glmmTMB(total_abund ~ treatment_code, data = recruitment.peak,
                       family = nbinom1())

plot(simulateResiduals(mod.recruit))

summary(mod.recruit)
